<subSubSection id="6EF2BB6B7BC13B48F7CB4CFBC4C5E70D" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="1F6367394C58D7149587C152D99FE4A8" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E66F200C08C55F5386C2E4789538685" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
A medium sized 
<taxonomicName id="21ACA4E4501B6F0B9DCE033E4AEE9667" class="Reptilia" family="Eublepharidae" genus="Eublepharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eublepharis" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E7B8C00AEA6FFA45E8AA2701D6794EB5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Eublepharis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reaching SVL of 140 mm, with 24 rows of flat, tubercle-like moderately keeled scales across the dorsum intermixed with much smaller scales, a single pale band between the nuchal loop and caudal constriction; smooth subdigital lamellae on digit IV of pes 17; 16 precloacal pores in an angulate series lacking a diastema.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DF12447C5348842ACFCD62FDEAAFA1E7" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="262F21FF454715FB630486F959479543" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E9A63B96F65ED322F29F94AC493C0681" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">The specific epithet is a patronym honoring Major-General Thomas Hardwicke (1756-1835) of the Bengal army of the East India Company.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="38A0184E19C86D1779B8236A4D6E1D57" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" type="description">
<paragraph id="3CC3403C0D1882D602E96A65C6A79480" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Description of holotype NHMUK 1946.8.26.6.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B48587958B800DE8D0BC6CF72C3A3785" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A4A9CE15FBDB7B389C20D9D9A6B5ACF5" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Eublepharis hardwickii holotype male NHMUK 1946.8.26.67 a. Dorsal view; b. Ventral view; c. Head dorsal view; d. Head ventral view; e. Lateral view. Scale bars: 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/688658" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">2</figureCitation>
): the type is in good condition of preservation, it is preserved in a linear 
<normalizedToken id="DB2FBCBB63013862F4B6CB5448F8DAFE" originalValue="‘S’">'S'</normalizedToken>
shaped manner. The anterior interocular region bears a deep grove, which may be an artifact of preservation or an injury.
</paragraph>
<caption id="C12933479B1D7D6C664C4BB85E9DFE08" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/688658" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="F6EF4A1CC0FB8187C47F79FD12E9B8ED" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis id="5D2CA45C786E59324E2D6F6933A62528" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Figure 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="36F97E8311D312851AC6612846D92215" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1827" class="Reptilia" family="Eublepharidae" genus="Eublepharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eublepharis hardwickii" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hardwickii">
<emphasis id="4F66D8D90A06CD12A80FDAE2113F3EB1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Eublepharis hardwickii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
holotype male NHMUK 1946.8.26.67 
<emphasis id="9C6CEAB59702A75358A348FBECC640DA" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">a.</emphasis>
Dorsal view; 
<emphasis id="AC61FF28A3A75B356241FCD113E146C2" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">b.</emphasis>
Ventral view; 
<emphasis id="2709704CB5403D1910EC61F4CBD0815C" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">c.</emphasis>
Head dorsal view; 
<emphasis id="193452991B8D149E85C00D44FAC0BA2A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">d.</emphasis>
Head ventral view; 
<emphasis id="9021AA45A3261139462529031F6CB2AB" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">e.</emphasis>
Lateral view. Scale bars: 20 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="FF929F1A6AB15CE18C61C57F6D97A85B" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/688659" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
<paragraph id="E76A9B034471D7B4B76235D71F6B0461" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis id="54A9C0AA1825EEB6DABFA75DD45919A8" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Figure 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="DB30E90A4A979414DD3935E1EE0F24F8" authorityName="Mirza &amp; Gnaneswar" authorityYear="2022" class="Reptilia" family="Eublepharidae" genus="Eublepharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eublepharis pictus" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pictus">
<emphasis id="A1C07C5F038CF363558A2F153AAC505C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Eublepharis pictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. holotype male NCBS NRC-AA-0015 
<emphasis id="E1514B8BB9995993040D4B1C8189EEFF" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">a.</emphasis>
Dorsal view; 
<emphasis id="08E2CBE893B42463A2473431C4FC954A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">b.</emphasis>
Ventral view; 
<emphasis id="A82763B604D3489B3C566464E97CFA5D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">c.</emphasis>
Head dorsal view; 
<emphasis id="7357F752CC627FB0D1D41F2E6B127194" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">d.</emphasis>
Head ventral view; 
<emphasis id="A2A1F06FD785BD6D87C8E6614BB47164" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">e.</emphasis>
Head lateral view. Scale bars: 20 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="CFFCB6AAB060C5ACBA5E1377886553F9" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
A large sized gecko (SVL 140 mm) with a fairly large head (HL/SVL ratio 0.14), head as long as wide (HW/HL ratio 0.99), head depressed (HH/HL ratio 0.58), distinct from neck (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="71CE3B2DA058DAC8C0745BF7B9092C7B" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Eublepharis hardwickii holotype male NHMUK 1946.8.26.67 a. Dorsal view; b. Ventral view; c. Head dorsal view; d. Head ventral view; e. Lateral view. Scale bars: 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/688658" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">2a, b</figureCitation>
); canthus rostralis inflated; snout short (SE/HW ratio 0.48), obtusely pointed from dorsal view and acutely in lateral view (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="38D83573316DC12555438BF9FD722F4E" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Eublepharis hardwickii holotype male NHMUK 1946.8.26.67 a. Dorsal view; b. Ventral view; c. Head dorsal view; d. Head ventral view; e. Lateral view. Scale bars: 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/688658" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">2c</figureCitation>
); longer than eye diameter (OD/SE ratio 0.51); scales on the snout heterogenous in shape and size, smaller ones with rounded edges and larger ones sub-hexagonal, convex; size of the scales increases in size towards the temporal region and are more flat intermixed with small rounded smooth scales. The scales post the temporal region are large, tubercle-like and sub-conical. These scales cover the dorsum of the animal, the hind limbs up-until the caudal constriction; eyes large (OD/HL ratio 0.25), pupil vertical with crenulated edges; supraciliaries 22, anterior ones smaller, these gradually increase in size and turn sub-conical from rounded towards the posterior portion; ear-opening large, sub-oval, obliquely oriented, smaller than orbital diameter (EL/OD ratio 0.77) lobules absent; eye to ear distance much greater than diameter of eye (EE/OD ratio 1.99); rostral quadrangle, much wider than deep, divided by a median suture for its entire length; rostral in contact with nasal, first supralabial and internasals; two large and a slightly smaller internasal between nasals, nostrils large situated medially in the nasal scale; mental sub-quadrangular, wider than long; (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2D3FBB4571EADA3D4553522245BAD5FE" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Eublepharis pictus sp. nov. paratype male NHMUK 1962.238 a. Dorsal view; b. Ventral view. Scale bars: 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/688660" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">4b</figureCitation>
); scales bordering the mental and infralabials large, gradually these reduce in size on throat up till the upper thoracic region, overall these scales are circular, convex, smaller than the ones ventral aspect of trunk; supralabials eleven on left and nine on right side; supralabials (to angle of jaw) twelve on either side; infralabials (to angle of jaw) nine on either sides.
</paragraph>
<caption id="87CE3703D20F9F519397C7132884D90D" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/688660" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph id="63843277BD0227F78D7750A116EB99A7" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis id="4ADCF487B3964F988263113F9A6741B8" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Figure 4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="E43F253B678E614D7B90C2AFA204BA19" authorityName="Mirza &amp; Gnaneswar" authorityYear="2022" class="Reptilia" family="Eublepharidae" genus="Eublepharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eublepharis pictus" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pictus">
<emphasis id="F1759E491E4889B51A55E71F0E2DDDBE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Eublepharis pictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. paratype male NHMUK 1962.238 
<emphasis id="C241792F7E9429B2FD265632AFCBCBFD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">a.</emphasis>
Dorsal view; 
<emphasis id="1FED5960A25A89BA1581AB8383673E58" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">b.</emphasis>
Ventral view. Scale bars: 20 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="06C1653F190DF7DD163AFD4F05B5A3AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
Body elongate (TRL/SVL ratio 0.33) and dorsoventrally flattened; lacking distinct ventrolateral furrow; dorsal scalation on trunk comprises of large sub-conical scales intermixed with small, round-edged flat scales, the large sub-conical scales are fairly arranged in 24 longitudinal rows at mid-body; ventral scales on trunk smooth, flat, smaller than dorsal scales; mid body scales across belly 26; a continuous series of 16 precloacal pores; (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="571056D04DDA7ABD4EDDC002E6488EA3" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Eublepharis hardwickii holotype male NHMUK 1946.8.26.67 a. Dorsal view; b. Ventral view; c. Head dorsal view; d. Head ventral view; e. Lateral view. Scale bars: 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/688658" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">2b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9450059259BF0AFC7165A9DA78ABBF57" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Limbs short, stout; digits bearing horizontally oriented smooth, un-notched lamellae on ventral surface; clawed, claw slightly smaller than length of the lamellar region; forelimbs short (FL/SVL ratio 0.09), equal in length with the hind limbs (CL/SVL ratio 0.10). Terminal phalanx of all digits curved, arising angularly from distal portion of expanded lamellar pad, free portion of phalanx of all digits half to more than half long as the dilated portion. Lamellae beneath the digits, right manus 8-12-13-14-12; right pes 8-13-15-17-16. Relative lengths of digits: III&gt;V&gt;IV&gt;II&gt;I (left manus), V&gt;II&gt;IV&gt;III&gt;I (left pes).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7584C67C83E2804DCAD999B50F76B7D5" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Tail stout, subtly flat on its ventral aspect, round in cross section, longer than snout-vent length (TL/SVL ratio 0.67). Caudal segments distinct on original tail; pholidosis of original tail dorsum with small, juxtaposed scales intermixed with large sub-conical tubercles in a whorl or 9-10 rows on the first segment, thereafter reduces in number on subsequent segments, scales on regenerated portion of tail heterogenous, lacking tubercles. Ventral aspect with large, broad scales, median row of scales not enlarged. Two sub-conical post cloacal spurs.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F00DFC3A9B99C9634561381372A39969" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="177BF99C0C1FCF107C0C616207D22D0B" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">Distribution and natural history</paragraph>
<paragraph id="41F9E468C140690A519578D3AE672393" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis id="5E691B02D392591D8CB99B62E4A8CC89" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4E59BB9F79F457CCF60B4AD08646BCC6" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Map of east India showing the distribution of E. hardwickii (black circles) and E. pictus sp. nov. (blue rhombus). Locality details for E. hardwickii (black numbers) 1. Chittagong, 2. Aushgram, 3. Chaibasa, 4. Barajamda, 5. Balasore; E. pictus sp. nov. (blue numbers) 1. Visakhapatnam, 2. Jaypore, 3. Kapilash, 4. Kandhamal, 5. Khurda, 6. Angul. Image of E. pictus sp. nov. by Gnaneshwar C. H." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/688661" pageId="0" pageNumber="77">5</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
The northernmost range of the species appears to be Aushgram in Burdwan district (West Bengal) is the northern most record of the species (
<bibRefCitation id="63524FEFED6BDBA4544C90A75802203A" author="Chandra, G" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" pagination="165 - 166" refId="B10" refString="Chandra, G, Chatterjee, S, Datta, C, Majumdar, M, Nath, A, 1997. Occurrence of the fat tailed gecko, Eublepharis hardwickii Grey (Sauria: Gekkonidae) with remarks on the variation in certain taxonomic characteristics. Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society 94: 165 - 166" title="Occurrence of the fat tailed gecko, Eublepharis hardwickii Grey (Sauria: Gekkonidae) with remarks on the variation in certain taxonomic characteristics." volume="94" year="1997">Chandra et al. 1997</bibRefCitation>
) and other records are from Chaibasa (
<bibRefCitation id="D4354C74C3A26AC26DB2C9A49F45BC7F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.5057" author="Cantor, T" journalOrPublisher="Saurologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" refId="B8" refString="Cantor, T, 1847. Catalogue of reptiles inhabiting the Malayan Peninsula and islands, collected or observed by Theodore Cantor, Esq., M. D. Bengal Medical Service. Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal 16: 607-656; 897-952; 1026-1078. [Pl. XIL-XL] https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.5057" title="Catalogue of reptiles inhabiting the Malayan Peninsula and islands, collected or observed by Theodore Cantor, Esq., M. D. Bengal Medical Service. Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal 16: 607 - 656; 897 - 952; 1026 - 1078. [Pl. XIL-XL]" url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.5057" year="1847">Cantor 1847</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="1CAC06F8C395F448E5AB420337F1FC17" author="Smith, MA" journalOrPublisher="Taylor and Francis, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" refId="B38" refString="Smith, MA, 1935. The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Reptilia and Amphibia. Vol. II. - Sauria. Taylor and Francis, London" title="The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Reptilia and Amphibia. Vol. II. - Sauria." year="1935">Smith 1935</bibRefCitation>
) and BNHS 855 Barajamda (Jharkhand) Belpahari (West Bengal) (
<bibRefCitation id="BDDE03D15F33E5CE67FE8B98F5BAB47D" author="Samanta, S" journalOrPublisher="Reptile Rap" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" pagination="25 - 26" refId="B36" refString="Samanta, S, Dutta, A, Kumar, B, Kumar, K, 2021. East Indian Leopard Gecko from the plateau region of West Bangal, India. Reptile Rap 213: 25 - 26" title="East Indian Leopard Gecko from the plateau region of West Bangal, India." volume="213" year="2021">Samanta et al. 2021</bibRefCitation>
) and Similipal (
<bibRefCitation id="C4DDFDE8CC016F0D135DFEB5A1C2BB67" author="Dutta, SK" journalOrPublisher="Regional Plant Resource Centre, Bhubaneswar" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" refId="B16" refString="Dutta, SK, Nair, MV, Mohapatra, PP, Mahapatra, A, 2009. Amphibians and Reptiles of Similipal Biosphere Reserve. Regional Plant Resource Centre, Bhubaneswar" title="Amphibians and Reptiles of Similipal Biosphere Reserve." year="2009">Dutta et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
) and Balasore (Odisha) (
<bibRefCitation id="D098D9B72C08AC3C7ED127339060C9D8" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2022.107414" author="Agarwal, I" pageId="0" pageNumber="77" refId="B2" refString="Agarwal, I, Bauer, AM, Gamble, T, Giri, VB, Jablonski, D, Khandekar, A, Mohapatra, PP, Masroor, R, Mishra, A, Ramakrishnan, U, 2022. The evolutionary history of an accidental model organism, the leopard gecko Eublepharis macularius (Squamata: Eublepharidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 168: 107414. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2022.107414" title="The evolutionary history of an accidental model organism, the leopard gecko Eublepharis macularius (Squamata: Eublepharidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 168: 107414." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2022.107414" year="2022">Agarwal et al. 2022</bibRefCitation>
) is the southernmost record of the species. Nothing is known about the biology of the species.
</paragraph>
